Confession. In Dublin, I WAS going to say hi to Rob & Maurice again on Sunday before my duo photo op. Wasn't busy. Instead, said I'd wait till AFTER the photo. I didn't get to speak to them again after, since tables were busy & I had to go to the airport after their panel. (1)

I don't LIKE mentioning that Rob and Maurice know who I am. I always feel like I'm bragging and that I look like I'm trying to big myself up, when there really isn't anything that special about me. I just wanted to show how kind they both were to me and how wonderful they are.

I kid you not. Maurice LaMarche recognised me in line for his autograph...and wouldn't accept my money. "Her money's no good here", he said. I tried to give him the money but he insisted it was free. Kind of felt like I'd committed a crime, but I was also genuinely touched. 🥺

I'm autistic too. It's VERY rare I have meltdowns, but I know how debilitating they can be. I certainly wouldn't want that in front of someone I admire (especially after losing something important!), and Rob and Maurice are such kind souls who could not have handled it better.
@Star4Frank @bauzilla They deemed him WHAT NOW???

Reason 101 why Rob Paulsen and Maurice LaMarche are the GOAT. They took what could have been a traumatic, embarrassing experience for a young autistic woman and turned it into something wonderful - both for Lucy, and everyone else.

Yes and no. I've definitely improved, but I'm definitely not at the level I want to be at yet. For example, I'd love to take commissions someday but I don't think I'm good enough.
For now, I draw for fun, and for education. I'm LEARNING to be a professional someday.
My least favourite thing to draw is BACKGROUNDS. Also fabric is an absolute bitch.

I use references a LOT. Don't let anyone tell you that this is cheating, because this is necessary for nearly EVERYTHING in art. There are some characters and poses I can draw from memory, but most of the time a reference is needed.

My favourite thing to draw? Fanart. Particularly of American cartoons - WB, Disney, etc. This is probably because I'm AWFUL at coming up with original ideas. Also, I adore 2D animating when I have the chance to do it.

I took art as a GCSE. This, however, concerned classical art and techniques. This was one of the things that made me think I wasn't cut out for art for a few years, as this kind of art wasn't my strong suit. Now an animation student at university, embracing the cartoony side!

I've been drawing since I was four. This was always a hobby of mine, but tended to be little doodles - eventually when I was around 16 I gave up, thinking that I wasn't good enough, only occasionally doodling here and there. I only started drawing properly again three years ago.
It varies. For more realistic artwork and sketches/small pieces, I prefer traditional. While if it's a comic or a bigger piece, digital. Also depends on my mood, I guess.

If either of you see this? Rob, Randy. Thank you both so much for your talent, humility, and going to so much trouble, even though I'm just one fan out of countless others. And Rob. Thank you for your unintentional comfort during such a dark time. Both then, and other times. 💖

Both Mr Paulsen and Mr Rogel went that extra mile for a nobody like me, when they did NOT have to. And Rob's "extra little gift", his little gesture, meant EVERYTHING to me when I was feeling absolutely hopeless. It almost felt like a hug, as cheesy as that sounds. (10)

So receiving this envelope was a MUCH needed comfort during what was probably the worst week of my life.

AND. It wasn't even Looped that sent this, like I'd expected. The envelope was in Rob's handwriting. He'd signed for and sent it to my house in the UK HIMSELF. (9)

I was speechless; I almost cried. It was not only a VERY kind gesture, but also? This was six days after my childhood best friend passed away. That morning had been particularly difficult, and I'd spent my train journey home trying not to break down in public. (8)
But THIS, too. The extra little gift: (7) https://t.co/ptnuaT2Dqw

Cut to October 2020 - when I got home after staying with my sister the night before, there was a large envelope from California. It had not only the new autograph from Rob and Randy (Just LOOK AT THIS): (6) https://t.co/5egBqjdmaq

A few days later, who should DM me but ROB FREAKING PAULSEN. He informed me that my new autograph had been returned to sender for some reason, and that he was sending it again "with an extra little gift" as thanks for my patience. (5)

He was shocked that I hadn't received my autograph yet - I think in hindsight it was lost in the post - and he thanked me for letting them know. He CC'd Rob and let me know that they'd sort this out, and was VERY kind to me. (4)

Someone provided me an email address to get in touch with the team who organised the event. Told them my autograph didn't show up, politely noting the pandemic/my location, thanked them. To my shock, *RANDY ROGEL*, cartoon-song-writing legend, replied. (3)

Meant to get an autograph from them both, them having signed it during the video call. Over a month passed, and I still hadn't received it. I thought, naturally it'd take a little longer since I live in the UK and there's a pandemic, but I still wanted to know what was up. (2)

Thought I'd share a story about @yakkopinky and @MrRandyRogel, and how much a simple gesture can matter.

August 2020, I met them via video call after their (amazing) virtual Animaniacs Live show. They were both LOVELY, I got to thank Rob for his support and kindness, etc. (1)
